Hi,

This is the cleaned CCU/NSI stack that let Radxa Cubie A7S boot past the
normal SDMMC0 IDMA failure path in local hardware testing. I am sending it as
RFC/RFT material because the touched clocks are introduced by the in-flight
A733 CCU support series.

The tested commit was:

    de486cb24c36 ("clk: sunxi-ng: a733: keep GIC and CPU peri clocks critical")

on top of:

    d9aa2e15caae

The boot-tested kernel reached:

  - clk_disable_unused()
  - unused power-domain disable
  - SDMMC0 host initialization
  - mmcblk0 partition discovery
  - read-only ext4 root mount
  - /bin/sh as init

The patches split the observed requirements into:

  1. keeping the CPUS/R-domain AHB bridge clock enabled;
  2. keeping the storage/NSI fabric clock bundle enabled;
  3. committing the boot-programmed NSI mux/divider state with the existing
     update-bit mechanism during CCU probe;
  4. keeping the GIC and CPU peripheral clocks enabled.

The narrowing tests removed ahb-iommu0-sys, ahb-iommu1-sys, and
pll-periph0-480M from the earlier diagnostic keepalive set while preserving the
successful boot. Removing both gic and cpu-peri, or keeping only one of them,
failed before root mount in the local test matrix.

The series is intentionally conservative. It preserves the hardware-proven
clock set rather than guessing at a narrower model that has not booted yet.

Enzo Adriano (4):
  clk: sunxi-ng: a733: keep the CPUS AHB bridge clock critical
  clk: sunxi-ng: a733: keep storage and NSI fabric clocks critical
  clk: sunxi-ng: a733: commit the boot-programmed NSI clock state
  clk: sunxi-ng: a733: keep GIC and CPU peri clocks critical

